Notes:
The intended impact of this activity is to increase the adoption and maintenance of malaria prevention
and treatment behaviors in targeted areas of Mozambique. By improving malaria related behavioral
outcomes, USAID expects to see a reduction in the overall malaria burden. The project aims to see
observable shifts in priority behaviors and enabling social norms including, but not limited to:
■ Correct and consistent use and care of insecticide-treated nets;
■ Prompt and appropriate care-seeking for fever;
■ Early and regular antenatal care attendance;
■ Acceptance of intermittent preventive treatment in pregnancy, when offered;
■ Acceptance of indoor residual spraying, when offered;
■ Adherence to national testing and treatment guidelines;
■ Adherence to malaria in pregnancy guidelines; and
■ Acceptance of new forms of prevention interventions.

The geographic scope of the project is Nationanwide, with focus on Provinces with Intermediary Warehouses and Regional/Central Warehouses, including the Provinces where DPMs will transition to Intermediary Warehouses. 

The Intermediary Warehouse Implementation, Central and Intermediate Warehouses Management and Accountability Project has six main objectives:

Implementation and operationalization of the strategy, processes, and procedures of intermediate warehouses.

Improved management of central and intermediate warehouses,  including minor infrastructure improvements;

Improved accountability and internal controls;

Improved security and communications capacity for CMAM Zimpeto warehouse;

Improvements to Zimpeto warehouse, including office space;

Improved stock control systems and security at Regional and Intermediate Warehouse
